    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-03-03T07:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-03-03T07:29:00-05:00" n="682"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d682">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/3998: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PDC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Poole</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Archangel</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-03-03T16:00:00+03:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 3, 1919, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 4, 2:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>922. A few days previously to French mutiny reported in my 920, March 2, 4 p.m.
                    British infantry company arriving among reenforcements <pb facs="0733" n="621"
                        xml:id="pg_621"/> from Murmansk refused to go to the front. Remained
                    recalcitrant until dealt with personally by <persName corresp="#p_IMGWE1"
                        >General Ironside</persName>. Several ringleaders now under arrest and may
                    have to be shot. Total of 121 French mutineers under arrest, <persName
                        corresp="#p_IMGWE1">Ironside</persName> insisting upon severe disciplinary
                    action against ringleaders. <persName corresp="#p_SCGE1">Colonel
                        Stewart</persName> tells me he expects to keep American battalion in hand by
                    drilling them himself during rest period. For the military attaché’s report see
                    his number 178 to military staff, Washington, dated March 3, 7 p.m.<note n="21"
                        xml:id="d682fn21">Not found in the files of the Department of State.</note>
                </p>
                <p>To Paris as number 53 same date.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PDC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Poole</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
